{{Orphan|date=August 2015}}

'''Just-in-time blocking''' is the practice of temporarily [[Block (Internet)|blocking]] [[internet access]] for people in a specific geographic area, to prevent them from accessing information or communicating with each other.

The first known instance of just-in-time blocking was documented by the [[OpenNet Initiative]] during the [[Kyrgyzstani parliamentary election, 2005|2005 Kyrgyz parliamentary elections]]. It's also been observed during the [[Belarusian presidential election, 2006|2006 Belarus presidential elections]], the [[Tajik presidential election, 2006|2006 Tajik presidential elections]], and is alleged to have taken place in [[Bahraini general election, 2006|Bahrain]], [[Ugandan general election, 2006|Uganda]], and [[Yemeni presidential election, 2006|Yemen]], during their 2006 presidential and parliamentary elections.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Deibert|first1=Ronald|title=Access Denied: The Practice and Policy of Global Internet Filtering|date=2008|publisher=The MIT Press|isbn=0262541963}}</ref> In 2016, internet watchdog organization [[Turkey Blocks]] identified two separate regional [[Internet shutdown|internet shutdowns]] commencing prior to the arrests of mayors in predominantly [[Kurds in Turkey|Kurdish]] [[Southeast Turkey|southeast of Turkey]], a mesaure believed to have been implemented by the government to prevent protests and limit critical media coverage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-turkey-security-internet-idUSKBN12Z0H4|title=Turkey blocks access to Twitter, Whatsapp: internet monitoring group|date=2016-11-04|work=Reuters|access-date=2017-05-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://turkeyblocks.org/2016/09/11/internet-shutdown-turkey-southeast/|title=Internet shutdown in Turkey's Southeast|date=2016-09-11|website=Turkey Blocks|access-date=2017-05-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://turkeyblocks.org/2016/10/27/new-internet-shutdown-turkey-southeast-offline-diyarbakir-unrest/|title=New internet shutdown in Turkey's Southeast: 8% of country now offline amidst Diyarbakir unrest|date=2016-10-27|website=Turkey Blocks|access-date=2017-05-03}}</ref>

In the two-week period leading up to the [[Iranian presidential election, 2013|2013 Iranian presidential elections]], anti-censorship groups [[Berkman Center for Internet & Society#Herdict|Herdict]] and [[ASL19]] found access to popular websites such as [[Facebook]], [[Meyar News]], [[Twitter]], the [[BBC]] and [[YouTube]] was intermittently blocked in Iran. [[Mohammad Hassan Nami]], then Iran’s [[Ministry of Information and Communications Technology of Iran|Minister of Communications and Information Technology]], told [[Tasnim News Agency]] that the restrictions were part of “security measures taken to preserve calm in the country during the election period."<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://poseidon01.ssrn.com/delivery.php?ID=754103009004067116110088127029100111121055086045016032125103095098083076089113119076096031059124007061000024000118092117100074024041045040023015011120090119126069041086007025081092081080070127071029091086007112069127099113110070023091090094118067029&EXT=pdf|title = INTERNET MONITOR 2013: Reflections on the Digital World|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref>

